<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="51" type="type">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="51">
USA, probably Arizona, near Gila river, June 1850, parasitic on 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Psorothamnus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Fabales" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="emoryi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Psorothamnus emoryi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(A. Gray) Rydb., 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">G. Thurber 682</emphasis>
(NY).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="51" type="note">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="51">
Tepals white, red to brown, in 3 whorls, each with 3 or 4 tepals, rarely more (Fig. 6B). Growing in branches of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Dalea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Fabales" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Dalea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Parosela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Fabales" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Parosela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rydberg" authorityYear="1919" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Psorothamnus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Fabales" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Psorothamnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the southern United States of America and Mexico (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Geographic distribution of Apodanthaceae based on label information from 785 herbarium collections." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10621" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Figs 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Phylogenetic relationships among the hosts of Apodanthaceae (legume relationships from Wojciechowski et al. 2006) and among the species of Apodanthaceae (from Bellot and Renner in review). Identical colors link parasite species and their host (s) and are also used in Figure 2. Dashed lines represent associations with rarely reported hosts; hosts in bold are the most common ones." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10622" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">3</figureCitation>
). New York (NY) has a specimen from Mexico of this species annotated as &quot; 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apodanthaceae" genus="Pilostyles" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mortoni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Pilostyles mortoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot;, a nomen nudum, by Ida de Vattimo in 1952.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
